 to prevention and health promotion is an example of how policy makers aim to rationalise and organise both health systems and patients' health practices. By applying a perspective from empirical science & technology studies (STS), based on qualitative research methods, the chapters of this book present a view behind the scenes and zoom into the micropolitics of prevention and health promotion. They analyse how patients are framed as being »at risk«, how preventative regimes shape medical practices, and what its practical consequences are in patients' everyday lives. This makes the insights of this book relevant for prevention and health promotion practitioners, public health policy-makers and researchers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHealth behavior. 0aHealth promotion. 0aPreventive health services. 4aBioethics. 4aBiopolitics. 4aHealth Promotion. 4aMedicine. 4aPractice. 4aScience and Technology Studies. 4aScience. 4aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBioethics.  aBiopolitics.  aHealth Promotion.  aMedicine.  aPractice.  aScience and Technology Studies.  aScience.  aSociology.1 aBeck, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupret Søndergaard, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuijer, Marli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Yvonne J.F.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Yvonne J.F.M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJonvallen, Petra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathar, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 